text.label: Text
text.value:
Vergerio was born in 1498 as the youngest of three brothers in what is now Koper, Slovenia, at a time when the city was called Iustinopolis and was under Venetian jurisdiction.
Little is known of his family; he may have been a distant relative of his namesake Pier Paolo Vergerio the Elder (1370-1444/45), a renowned 15th-century humanist who played a prominent role at the Council of Constance.

text.label: Text
text.value: He studied (civil) law in Padua and was awarded the title of Dr. iuris and poeta laureatus. He practised as a lawyer for just over seven years. Then - after the death of his wife - he turned to ecclesiastical diplomacy.

text.label: Text
text.value: It is uncertain whether Vergerio's wife Diana Contarini was related to the famous Gasparo Contarini; there was also a prominent family of Contarinis in Koper. He met his wife in Venice and married her in 1526, but she died in April or May 1527. This must have shaken Vergerio, as after his wife's death he decided to become an ordained priest.

text.label: Text
text.value: Highly educated and with previous connections to the papal court (his elder brother Aurelio had been a secretary to the pope), Vergerio aimed for higher office in the church organisation. In 1530 he came to Rome where he won the trust of Pope Clemens VII and became his secretary. As such, he would travel extensively throughout the German lands to secure support for the Ecumenical Council.

text.label: Text
text.value: During his trips to Germany, Vergerio also met Martin Luther. He was less than enthusiastic about his first meeting with Martin Luther: "He seems younger than he really is, but has the eyes of a madman," he wrote to one of his confidants. He was also displeased by Luther's insistence on the location of the future ecumenical council.

title.label: Title
title.value: From a diplomatic failure to an unimportant bishop

text.label: Text
text.value: Since the German autonomous cities did not accept the Pope's proposal for the location of the Ecumenical Council, Vergerio's diplomatic mission proved a failure. He was also suspected of being sympathetic to some Protestant ideas. Nevertheless, his political patron, the Holy Roman Emperor Ferdinand I, didn't forget his services: in 1536 he appointed him Bishop of Modru in Croatia and, later that year, Bishop of Iustinopolis, although he wanted the more important neighbouring city of Trieste.

question.label: Question
question.value: What do you think, which house did Ferdinand I belong to?

text.label: Text
text.value: Despite his reluctance to come to an unimportant city like his native Iustinopolis, Vergerio carried out his ministry with passion and zeal. Perhaps this is why he was accused of heresy by the clergy of his own diocese. His lawsuit against Antonio Elio, Alessandro Farnese's secretary, made matters worse: Vergerio refused to pay Elio an annual stipend of 50 ducats (a quarter of his annual income), and so Elio - and the Farnese family - became Vergerio's bitter enemies.

text.label: Text
text.value: In 1548, Vergerio had had enough. After nearly eight years of fighting accusations and charges, he left Italy for good. He first found refuge in Switzerland, from where he moved to Wittemberg, where he became Duke Christoph's personal advisor and envoy, and (again) travelled extensively through German lands. However, he continued to infiltrate Italy incognito to distribute his books, in which he fiercely attacked the papal court.

text.label: Text
text.value: Throughout his years in Germany, Vergerio worked closely with prominent humanists, including Primus Trubar, another refugee from Slovenian lands. Together they worked on the first Slovenian translations of the Bible and other liturgical texts, and despite their differences, it was Trubar who sat by Vergerio's deathbed when he died in 1565.

text.label: Text
text.value: Sometimes the middle ages were as bad as their reputation: In 897, a "horrible convention" (synodus horrenda) took place in Rome: Pope Stephen VI. had the dead body of his predecessor Pope Formosus excavated and put on trial. Formosus was convicted posthumously of heresy - and his body was thrown into the Tiber river.

text.label: Text
text.value: But this was not an isolated case - 600 years later a similar fate happened to Pier Paolo Vergerio. He was not a pope, but a bishop and reformer - just like his more famous colleague Martin Luther. Curious? Here comes his story!

text.label: Text
text.value: The Popes Formose and Stephen VI (painting by Jean-Paul Laurens)

text.label: Text
text.value: Only about ten years after Vergerio's death, the town of Iustinopolis became "the second Rome": A synodus horrenda of its own kind took place there. The younger of the three Vergerii, Giambattista and Pier Paolo, were excommunicated for the second time. Giambattista's bones, buried in the Cathedral, were dug up and thrown into the sea, while his and Pier Paolo's names were erased from the inscription commemorating the eldest of the three, Aurelio. The only epigraphic trace of Vergerio is therefore the inscription in Wittemberg. But also his literary remains will remind us of his impressive life and work.

text.label: Text
text.value: Erased Inscription in the Cathedral of the Assumption (Koper)

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E1.description: He was born at Capodistria (Koper), Istria, then part of the Venetian Republic IMG[Image of him]

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E2.description: Despite their previous fallout, Trubar is present at Vergerio's deathbed

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E3.description: He studied jurisprudence in Padua; was awarded the title dr. iuris and poeta laureatus

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E4.description: Worked as a lawyer, the longest period in Venice (5 years)

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E5.description: In Venice he met and married Diana Contarini; she died a year later

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E6.description: In 1530 he came to Rome, where he won the trust of Pope Clemens VII

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E7.description: Papal nuntio for Pope Clemens VII

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E8.description: Travelled extensively to German towns in preparations for the ecumenical council under Pope Paul III

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E9.description: He met Martin Luther personally and disliked him

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E10.description: Participated in the committee for the drafting of the Papal decree on the convening of the ecumenical council (led by Gasparo Contarini) titled Ad dominici gregis curam

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E11.description: Was awarded the bishopric in Modru and Senj for his services as papal nuntio

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E12.description: Was awarded the bishopric in his hometown of Iustinopolis (Koper) at behest of Emperor Ferdinand; travels extensively to Istria Dalmatia and the East; fallout and legal process against Antonio Elio, secretary to Alessandro Farnese

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E13.description: Together with Hipolito d'Este travels to French court, has ties to the sister of Francis I, Marguerite of Navarre

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E14.description: Travels to Worms (and Haguenau?) to take part in the conference

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E15.description: Active reformist in his bishopric of Iustinopolis, but also suspected to be introducing Lutheranism to Istria

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E16.description: Officially charged by the Franciscan pater-guardian of Lutheranism and recalled to Rome; moves to Mantua to Cardinal Gonzaga in order to avoid inquisition

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E17.description: Charges dropped; Vergerio wrote his famous Otto difesioni

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E18.description: Charges against Vergerio were renewed in 1548

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E20.description: Pope officially excommunicated Vergerio in absentia

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E22.description: Moves to Tubingen to become adviser to Christoph, Duke of Wrttemberg

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E23.description: Wrote more than 170 works (mostly anti-papal pamphlets); worked closely with P. Trubar who translated the Bible into Slovene; V. also actively promoted the translation of the Bible into Croatian (with little success)

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E24.description: An overly ambitious man, V. credited himself with too big a role in the translations of the Bible into vernacular languages

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E25.description: Diplomatic missions to Poland on behalf of Christoph, Duke of Wrttemberg

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E26.description: Diplomatic missions to Poland on behalf of Christoph, Duke of Wrttemberg

data-vergerio-tagging-bio-E27.description: The inscription in the Cathedral of the Assumption in Koper is partially demolished, probably at behest of the then bishop Antonio Elio
